I am building a Jitsi conference server in DreamObjects as this helped me quickly build a conferencing solution to satisfy the local government needs in the US, and you can find the repo with the source code and instructions on https://github.com/dbland51/conferenceserver. Currently I’m using a modified version of the ejabbered docker container by running 2 ejabberd processes – one for jicofo, and the other one for jvb. The ejabberd docker containers expose a few ports (5222 mutliuser chat, 5269 & 5280 conference video/voice), bind mount your user dir (copy your JWT id & created domain from jicofo config file) so that user accounts and domain name are propagated to the users directory, mount the local filesystem containing a custom SSL cert/key, and publish 3 Docker networks: jicofo, jvb, and the rest. Each of these networks will contain a number of containers, including the ejabberd nodes, a mysql database (containing 1 table with 6 columns, all of them varchar(100)), an nginx container to help facilitate the conference, and 5 Riot rooms (WebRTC video/voice chat). You can see there is not much going on in the implementation, but there is a fair bit of security settings and coordination that you will need to know prior to implementing. Two of those considerations is the importance of using a full domain, not subdomain (so account would be: conference.domain-public.com and not, for example, conf.domain-public.com) to avoid conflicts with other domains, and secondly is to make sure you have access to the appropriate ports on your firewall as each of these features has it

